<font color="#FF0000">SLIDING BACK</font><br>
<tt>Sun Nov  2  1:50:45 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
There were many losses that affected my life.  Particularly the loss of a friend in a fiery crash.  I can't blame any of that on Nam.  The near death experiences even some where I knew I was dead, but figured what the hell; I will not die easy.  My encounter with a MIG 21 one dark night left no real imprint. These are memories, but they no longer haunt me.<br><br>
The voices of other men in their final moments haunt on quiet nights.  Their voices, their agony I remember.  I am sure now those things that happened to me have no impact.  The feeling of not being able to help just will not go away.<br><br>
Sudden jolts of air turbulence drive me crazy. (Wonder why)  I can no longer stand heights.  I like to be alone a lot.  I hate crowds and can not tolerate noisy rooms.  I hate missing the first six years of my marriage and the younger years of my boys.<br><br>
I find it easier too talk to vets even when we never talk about war.  I believe we sense it all somehow.<br><br>
I struggle with a feeling of contempt for the Pacific Rim mentality.  My oldest son who is Asia now just finished (by phone) telling me about a group of people standing around while one of them beat another to death with a shovel.<br><br>
Sometimes I need to shut it out, but his phone call brought it all back.<br>

